// NCMHCE — Part 4 (Q211-300)
var _qs = window.QUESTIONS_DATA["ncmhce"] || (window.QUESTIONS_DATA["ncmhce"] = []);

_qs.push(
{id:"ncm-211",q:"A 35-year-old client with PTSD has been experiencing nightmares and hypervigilance. The counselor should FIRST:",options:["Begin exposure immediately","Build the relationship, provide psychoeducation, develop coping skills (grounding, breathing, sleep hygiene), and use a phased approach to trauma treatment","Refer to a psychiatrist only","Tell the client they're fine"],answer:1,explanation:"PTSD: phased approach. Phase 1: stabilization (rapport, psychoeducation, coping skills, sleep hygiene, grounding, breathing, emotion regulation, support, safety). Phase 2: processing (PE, EMDR, CPT) when stable. Phase 3: integration. Don't begin exposure without stabilization. Don't refer only to a psychiatrist. Don't dismiss. The relationship and the skills are the foundation. SSRIs (sertraline, paroxetine) are first-line medications; coordinate with the prescriber."},
{id:"ncm-212",q:"A 20-year-old client has been in a motorcycle accident and is now having flashbacks. The counselor should:",options:["Begin trauma processing immediately","Use the phased approach: stabilization, processing (PE, EMDR, or CPT), and integration","Refer to a psychiatrist only","Hospitalize"],answer:1,explanation:"Acute trauma + flashbacks: phased approach. Stabilize first (safety, sleep, coping, support, regulation), then process the trauma memory (PE, EMDR, CPT), then integrate. Don't begin trauma processing without stabilization. Don't refer only to a psychiatrist. Don't hospitalize (unless imminent risk). The work is paced, careful, and trauma-informed. Many people recover well with proper treatment. The counselor's role is critical. Avoid retraumatization."},
{id:"ncm-213",q:"A 12-year-old has been exhibiting symptoms of PTSD after a car accident. The counselor should:",options:["Use TF-CBT (Trauma-Focused CBT) with the child and family, beginning with stabilization and progressing through trauma narrative and processing","Use EMDR immediately","Refer to a psychiatrist only","Tell the child to forget it"],answer:1,explanation:"Child PTSD: TF-CBT is first-line. The PRACTICE model: Psychoeducation, Relaxation, Affect modulation, Cognitive processing, Trauma narrative, In vivo mastery, Conjoint sessions, Enhancing future safety. Don't use EMDR immediately. Don't refer only to a psychiatrist. Don't dismiss. Engage the family. Many children benefit. Trauma-informed care. The counselor's role is to support the child, engage the family, and use evidence-based treatment. The work is paced, careful, and developmentally appropriate."},
{id:"ncm-214",q:"A 40-year-old client with bipolar disorder has been stable on lithium for 5 years. They are now considering pregnancy. The counselor should:",options:["Tell them to stop lithium","Address the risk/benefit of medication in pregnancy, coordinate with the prescriber and OB, support informed decision-making, and address mood monitoring","Hospitalize","Recommend they not have children"],answer:1,explanation:"Pregnancy and bipolar: address the risk/benefit of medication (lithium is associated with cardiac malformations in the first trimester; valproate and carbamazepine are higher risk; lamotrigine and some atypicals may be safer). Coordinate with the prescriber and OB. Support informed decision-making. Address mood monitoring (postpartum is high risk for bipolar relapse). Don't tell them to stop (relapse risk). Don't hospitalize. Don't recommend against children. The counselor supports informed choice. Address: pre-conception counseling, medication planning, monitoring, support, and postpartum planning."},
{id:"ncm-215",q:"A 30-year-old client has been in therapy for 3 months for depression. The counselor notices the client's affect is suddenly bright and they have been sleeping less. The counselor should:",options:["Congratulate them","Assess for hypomania/mania, ask about medication adherence, and coordinate with the prescriber","Discharge","Tell them they're cured"],answer:1,explanation:"Sudden change in depression treatment: assess for hypomania/mania. May indicate bipolar disorder, medication-induced mood elevation, or other causes. Ask about medication adherence (antidepressants can trigger mania in bipolar). Coordinate with the prescriber. Don't congratulate. Don't discharge. Don't tell them they're cured. The counselor's observation is critical. Many clients with bipolar are first diagnosed as having unipolar depression. Address: sleep, mood, energy, activity, thought patterns, and risk. Document. The differential matters for treatment."},
{id:"ncm-216",q:"A 19-year-old client has been engaging in self-harm to manage overwhelming emotions. The counselor should:",options:["Tell them to stop","Use DBT (Dialectical Behavior Therapy): distress tolerance, emotion regulation, interpersonal effectiveness, and mindfulness. Address the function of self-harm.","Hospitalize for every episode","Refer to a psychiatrist only"],answer:1,explanation:"Self-harm: DBT is evidence-based. The four modules: distress tolerance (TIPP, ACCEPTS, self-soothing, distraction), emotion regulation (identify and label emotions, reduce vulnerability, increase positive events, opposite action), interpersonal effectiveness (DEAR MAN, GIVE, FAST), and mindfulness (Observe, Describe, Participate; Non-judgmentally; One-mindfully; Effectively). Address the function of self-harm. Don't tell them to stop. Don't hospitalize for every episode. Don't refer only to a psychiatrist. The counselor's role is central. Many clients learn better ways to manage distress."},
{id:"ncm-217",q:"A 35-year-old client has been sober for 3 years. They are now struggling with anxiety. The counselor should:",options:["Tell them to focus on recovery","Address the anxiety with CBT, mindfulness, and possibly medication referral. Coordinate with the recovery support system.","Recommend more AA meetings","Hospitalize"],answer:1,explanation:"Anxiety in recovery: treat it. CBT, mindfulness, and possibly SSRIs/SNRIs (buspirone is also an option). Coordinate with the recovery support system. Don't dismiss. Don't recommend more AA (it doesn't treat anxiety). Don't hospitalize (rarely appropriate for anxiety alone). Many people in recovery develop anxiety disorders. The counselor addresses the whole person. Address: triggers, function, coping, sleep, and support. Treat comorbidities. Recovery is holistic."},
{id:"ncm-218",q:"A 30-year-old client has been in an abusive relationship. They are now ready to leave. The counselor should:",options:["Tell them to leave immediately","Provide safety planning, resources, and support the client's autonomy. Engage the advocate and legal system as appropriate.","Tell them to stay for the children","Recommend couples therapy"],answer:1,explanation:"Ready to leave an abusive relationship: provide safety planning (when, where, what to bring, who to tell, where to go), resources (hotline, shelter, legal advocacy), and support the client's autonomy. Engage the advocate and legal system as appropriate. Don't tell them to leave (the client decides). Don't tell them to stay. Don't recommend couples therapy (unsafe; the abuser often blames the victim). Provide options. The client decides. Many people leave multiple times before leaving for good. Safety is the first priority."},
{id:"ncm-219",q:"A 25-year-old client has been experiencing severe anxiety, panic attacks, and agoraphobia. The counselor should:",options:["Recommend benzodiazepines","Use CBT: psychoeducation, cognitive restructuring, interoceptive exposure, in vivo exposure (develop a hierarchy), and relapse prevention. Consider SSRIs.","Tell them to avoid feared situations","Hospitalize"],answer:1,explanation:"Panic and agoraphobia: CBT is first-line. Components: psychoeducation (the cycle of panic, the role of avoidance), cognitive restructuring (catastrophic misinterpretations), interoceptive exposure (deliberately inducing panic sensations), in vivo exposure (hierarchy of feared situations, gradual), and relapse prevention. SSRIs are first-line medication. Don't recommend benzos (dependence, fall risk, can worsen long-term). Don't tell them to avoid (reinforces fear). Don't hospitalize (rarely appropriate). The counselor supports the client through exposure. Many people improve with proper treatment."},
{id:"ncm-220",q:"A 12-year-old has been exhibiting symptoms of mania (decreased need for sleep, grandiosity, racing thoughts). The counselor should:",options:["Refer for urgent psychiatric evaluation and provide psychoeducation, family support, and ongoing therapy","Tell the child to calm down","Hospitalize for several months","Refer to a different counselor"],answer:1,explanation:"Child mania: refer for urgent psychiatric evaluation (child psychiatry). May be bipolar I or II, or other conditions. Provide psychoeducation, family support, and ongoing therapy (CBT for child bipolar, family-focused therapy, multi-family psychoeducation). Coordinate with the school. Don't tell the child to calm down. Don't hospitalize for several months. Don't refer to a different counselor. The counselor's role is key. Many children with bipolar do well with proper treatment. Address: safety, mood, sleep, family, school, and monitoring."},
{id:"ncm-221",q:"A 45-year-old client has been in treatment for severe depression for 1 year with good progress. The counselor should:",options:["Terminate immediately","Discuss maintenance, relapse prevention, and termination collaboratively. The relationship is the basis for the work.","Increase session frequency","Tell the client they're cured"],answer:1,explanation:"Long-term recovery: discuss maintenance (continue for a while to consolidate), relapse prevention (warning signs, coping skills, supports, professional numbers), and termination collaboratively. Don't terminate immediately. Don't increase frequency unnecessarily. Don't tell the client they're cured (depression often recurs). The relationship is the basis. Many clients benefit from maintenance. The counselor supports the client's continued growth and well-being. End well. The work is rarely 'done' — it evolves."},
{id:"ncm-222",q:"A 30-year-old client has been sober for 6 months. They have been engaging in self-harm. The counselor should:",options:["Tell them to choose one issue","Use DBT (which can be combined with substance use treatment — DBT-SUD), address both issues, and coordinate with the treatment team","Hospitalize","Refer to AA only"],answer:1,explanation:"Co-occurring self-harm and substance use: DBT-SUD combines DBT skills with substance use treatment. Address both issues simultaneously. Don't tell them to choose. Don't hospitalize. Don't refer only to AA. The counselor coordinates the treatment team. Many clients with co-occurring disorders have more severe issues and need integrated treatment. DBT-SUD is evidence-based. The counselor's role: skills, support, and coordination. Address: triggers, function, alternative coping, and recovery support."},
{id:"ncm-223",q:"A 12-year-old has been engaging in repetitive checking (locks, doors, switches). The counselor should:",options:["Tell the child to stop","Conduct a multi-informant assessment, develop a fear hierarchy, and begin ERP (with the parents as co-therapists). SSRIs may be considered.","Refer to a psychiatrist only","Hospitalize"],answer:1,explanation:"Child OCD: multi-informant assessment, family engagement, fear hierarchy, and ERP (with parents as co-therapists). SSRIs (fluoxetine, fluvoxamine, sertraline) are first-line medication in children 8+. Don't tell the child to stop. Don't refer only to a psychiatrist. Don't hospitalize. Family-based CBT for OCD is evidence-based. The counselor's patience and the family's support are critical. Many children with OCD improve with proper treatment. Address: family accommodation, school, peers, and self-esteem."},
{id:"ncm-224",q:"A 50-year-old client has been experiencing menopause and is having significant mood swings. The counselor should:",options:["Tell them it's normal","Provide support, address the hormonal changes, use CBT, consider medical consultation, and treat the mood symptoms","Refer to a psychiatrist only","Hospitalize"],answer:1,explanation:"Perimenopause/menopause mood changes: provide support, address the hormonal changes, use CBT, consider medical consultation (gynecology, primary care, possibly a hormone specialist). Treat the mood symptoms (depression, anxiety, irritability). Many women experience mood symptoms during this transition. Don't dismiss. Don't refer only to a psychiatrist. Don't hospitalize (rarely appropriate). The counselor addresses the whole person. Hormones, life changes (aging, children leaving, parents aging), and mood are all connected. Treat the whole person."},
{id:"ncm-225",q:"A 25-year-old client has been struggling with an eating disorder for 10 years. The counselor should:",options:["Tell them they're chronic","Address the eating disorder, comorbidities, and the long history with evidence-based treatment (CBT-E, FBT for younger adults, possibly DBT for emotion regulation). Coordinate with the medical team.","Hospitalize","Refer to a different counselor"],answer:1,explanation:"Long-standing eating disorder: address the eating disorder, comorbidities (depression, anxiety, OCD, substance, personality), and the long history. Use evidence-based treatment (CBT-E, FBT for younger clients, possibly DBT for emotion regulation). Coordinate with the medical team. Don't tell them they're chronic. Don't hospitalize. Don't refer away. Many people with long-standing eating disorders improve with sustained work. The counselor's role: support, treatment, and hope. Address: family, relationships, body image, and the meaning of recovery."},
{id:"ncm-226",q:"A 35-year-old client with chronic mental illness has been in supported housing. They want to live independently. The counselor should:",options:["Tell them they can't","Assess functioning, develop a plan, coordinate with ACT or case management, and support the client's goal","Hospitalize","Recommend a different program"],answer:1,explanation:"Recovery goal: independent living. Assess functioning, develop a plan (housing, finances, daily living, social support, mental health care), coordinate with ACT or case management. The counselor supports the client's goal. Don't dismiss. Don't hospitalize. Don't recommend a different program. Many people with chronic mental illness can live independently with proper support. Housing First is evidence-based. Address: skills, support, resources, and the meaning of home. The counselor's role: hope, support, and advocacy."},
{id:"ncm-227",q:"A 14-year-old has been struggling with gender dysphoria. The counselor should:",options:["Recommend a specific path","Provide an affirming approach, support the client's exploration, engage the family, provide resources, and address any co-occurring issues","Refer to a conversion therapist","Tell them they'll grow out of it"],answer:1,explanation:"Adolescent gender dysphoria: affirmative approach. Support the client's exploration of identity. Engage the family (parents, siblings, extended). Provide resources (WPATH standards of care, GLAAD, HRC, PFLAG, Trans Lifeline). Address any co-occurring issues (depression, anxiety, trauma, bullying). Don't recommend a specific path (the client decides). Don't refer to conversion therapy (unethical, harmful). Don't tell them they'll grow out of it (often persistent; can worsen with dismissal). Many transgender youth benefit from affirming care. Address: school, peers, family, body, and identity."},
{id:"ncm-228",q:"A 30-year-old client has been experiencing severe anxiety and has been unable to leave the house for 6 months. The counselor should:",options:["Tell them to push through","Use CBT with graded exposure: build a hierarchy, develop coping skills, and gradually engage the client in activities outside the home","Hospitalize","Recommend they stay home"],answer:1,explanation:"Agoraphobia: CBT with graded exposure is first-line. Build a hierarchy (e.g., step outside, walk to the end of the driveway, walk to the corner, etc.). Develop coping skills (breathing, cognitive restructuring, problem-solving). Gradually engage. SSRIs are first-line medication. Don't tell them to push through (anxiety is real). Don't hospitalize. Don't recommend they stay home. The counselor supports the client through the exposure. Many people improve with proper treatment. Address: family, work, friends, and the meaning of engagement."},
{id:"ncm-229",q:"A 45-year-old client has been dealing with chronic pain for 10 years. The counselor should:",options:["Tell them to manage without medication","Use CBT for chronic pain: pacing, activity, sleep, mood, coping, and thoughts. Coordinate with the pain team.","Hospitalize","Recommend opioids"],answer:1,explanation:"Chronic pain: CBT is evidence-based. Components: pacing (gradual increase in activity), activity scheduling, sleep hygiene, mood (depression, anxiety), coping (relaxation, distraction), thoughts (catastrophizing, fear-avoidance). Coordinate with the pain team (medical, OT/PT, sometimes pain psychology). Don't tell them to manage without medication (pain is real). Don't hospitalize. Don't recommend opioids (CDC guidelines, risks). The counselor addresses the whole person. The functional goal is improvement in function, not zero pain. Address: family, work, identity, and meaning."},
{id:"ncm-230",q:"A 12-year-old has been exhibiting severe separation anxiety. The counselor should:",options:["Tell the child to be brave","Conduct a multi-informant assessment, engage the family, use CBT (gradual exposure, cognitive restructuring, parent training), and consider SSRIs","Hospitalize","Recommend homeschooling"],answer:1,explanation:"Child separation anxiety: multi-informant assessment, family engagement, CBT (gradual exposure, cognitive restructuring, parent training — e.g., Cool Kids program). SSRIs (fluoxetine, fluvoxamine) are first-line medication. Don't tell the child to be brave. Don't hospitalize. Don't recommend homeschooling (worsens anxiety). The counselor's role: support, family work, and skills. Many children improve with proper treatment. Address: school, family, peers, and the meaning of separation. Pace matters."},
{id:"ncm-231",q:"A 25-year-old client has been struggling with severe anxiety for years. The counselor should:",options:["Begin intensive CBT immediately","Conduct a comprehensive assessment, address comorbidities, use CBT (cognitive restructuring, exposure), consider SSRIs, and develop a long-term plan","Hospitalize","Tell them to relax"],answer:1,explanation:"Long-standing anxiety: comprehensive assessment, address comorbidities (depression, substance, OCD, PTSD, medical), use CBT (cognitive restructuring, exposure), consider SSRIs. Develop a long-term plan. Don't begin intensive CBT without assessment. Don't hospitalize (rarely appropriate for anxiety alone). Don't tell them to relax (dismissive). The counselor's role: support, treatment, and hope. Many people with long-standing anxiety improve with proper treatment. Address: triggers, function, coping, sleep, and the meaning of safety."},
{id:"ncm-232",q:"A 30-year-old client has been in treatment for severe depression for 1 year. The counselor should:",options:["Terminate immediately","Discuss maintenance, relapse prevention, and termination collaboratively. The relationship is the basis for the work.","Increase session frequency","Tell the client they're cured"],answer:1,explanation:"Long-term recovery: discuss maintenance (continue for a while to consolidate), relapse prevention (warning signs, coping skills, supports, professional numbers), and termination collaboratively. Don't terminate immediately. Don't increase frequency. Don't tell the client they're cured (depression often recurs). The relationship is the basis. Many clients benefit from maintenance. The counselor supports the client's continued growth and well-being. End well. Address: identity, meaning, and the future."},
{id:"ncm-233",q:"A 14-year-old has been engaging in self-harm and has been admitted to a hospital. The counselor should:",options:["Discharge as soon as possible","Continue to engage the client in the hospital, develop a safety plan, address underlying issues, and plan for transition to ongoing treatment","Tell the teen they're fine","Refer to a different counselor"],answer:1,explanation:"Hospitalized teen with self-harm: continue to engage the client in the hospital, develop a safety plan, address underlying issues (DBT, family therapy, individual therapy), and plan for transition to ongoing treatment (intensive outpatient, residential, or outpatient). Don't discharge as soon as possible. Don't dismiss. Don't refer away. The counselor's role: support, treatment, and continuity. The hospital is a brief stabilization, not a destination. The transition is high-risk. Address: family, school, peers, and the meaning of recovery."},
{id:"ncm-234",q:"A 35-year-old client has been in recovery from alcohol use disorder for 2 years. They are now struggling with work-related stress. The counselor should:",options:["Tell them to focus on recovery","Develop a stress management plan (without substances), address triggers, maintain recovery support, and use coping skills","Recommend inpatient","Hospitalize"],answer:1,explanation:"Work stress in recovery: develop a stress management plan (without substances), address triggers, maintain recovery support (sponsor, AA, friends), use coping skills (relaxation, exercise, social support, problem-solving), and ensure self-care. Don't tell them to focus on recovery. Don't recommend inpatient. Don't hospitalize. Many people in recovery manage work stress. The counselor supports the client's continued recovery and quality of life. Address: work environment, relationships, sleep, and the meaning of balance."},
{id:"ncm-235",q:"A 25-year-old client has been engaging in risky sexual behavior. The counselor should:",options:["Tell them to be abstinent","Use MI to explore the behavior, address risk reduction (condom use, STI testing, contraception), and discuss values and goals","Refer to a doctor only","Hospitalize"],answer:1,explanation:"Risky sexual behavior: MI, explore the behavior, address risk reduction (condom use, STI testing, contraception, PrEP for HIV if appropriate), discuss values and goals, address substance use (often related). Don't demand abstinence. Don't refer only to a doctor. Don't hospitalize. Many young people engage in risky behavior. Address: consent, pleasure, relationships, decision-making, self-efficacy, and self-worth. Harm reduction is ethical and effective. Engage the client with respect."},
{id:"ncm-236",q:"A 12-year-old has been exhibiting symptoms of depression. The counselor should:",options:["Recommend medication only","Provide education, engage the family, support psychotherapy for the child (CBT, IPT-A, family therapy, play therapy as appropriate), and consider medication evaluation","Tell the parents to wait","Hospitalize"],answer:1,explanation:"Child depression: education, family engagement, psychotherapy (CBT, IPT-A, family therapy, play therapy as appropriate), consider medication evaluation (SSRIs are first-line in children 8+; fluoxetine is the only FDA-approved antidepressant for children; refer to child psychiatry for medication management). Don't recommend medication only. Don't tell the parents to wait. Don't hospitalize. Address: school, family, peers, sleep, exercise, screen time. Many effective treatments. Engage the child and family."},
{id:"ncm-237",q:"A 35-year-old client has been dealing with chronic depression for 10 years. The counselor should:",options:["Recommend a quick fix","Provide long-term support, evidence-based therapy (CBT, BA, MBCT, IPT), coordinate with the prescriber, and address chronic issues","Hospitalize","Discharge as chronic"],answer:1,explanation:"Chronic depression: long-term approach. Provide evidence-based therapy (CBT, behavioral activation, MBCT, IPT, CBT for chronic depression). Coordinate with the prescriber. Address: chronic issues, comorbidity, life stress, sleep, exercise, social connection. Don't promise a quick fix. Don't hospitalize (not appropriate for chronic stable depression). Don't discharge as 'chronic' (that abandons the client). Many people with chronic depression can improve with sustained work. The relationship is therapeutic. Stay involved. Don't give up."},
{id:"ncm-238",q:"A 14-year-old has been engaging in self-harm. The parents are in denial. The counselor should:",options:["Tell the parents the teen is fine","Address the self-harm, engage the family, provide education, develop a safety plan, and provide family therapy","Hospitalize","Discharge the case"],answer:1,explanation:"Self-harm with parental denial: address the self-harm, engage the family, provide education (what self-harm is, what it isn't, what the teen needs), develop a safety plan, and provide family therapy. Don't tell the parents the teen is fine. Don't hospitalize (unless imminent risk). Don't discharge. The counselor's role: engage the family, address the family dynamics (denial, shame, fear), and provide treatment. Many parents of self-harming teens struggle with guilt, fear, and shame. The work is to engage them and provide treatment. The teen's safety is the first priority."},
{id:"ncm-239",q:"A 30-year-old client has been in treatment for anxiety for 3 months. The counselor should:",options:["Terminate treatment","Continue treatment, reassess progress, develop a relapse prevention plan, and discuss maintenance and termination collaboratively","Increase the dose","Tell them they're cured"],answer:1,explanation:"Anxiety treatment at 3 months: continue treatment, reassess progress, develop a relapse prevention plan (warning signs, coping skills, supports, professional numbers), and discuss maintenance and termination collaboratively. Don't terminate prematurely. Don't increase unnecessarily. Don't tell them they're cured. The work is to consolidate the gains, prepare for setbacks, and end well. Many clients benefit from booster sessions. The counselor supports the client's growth and continued well-being. Address: triggers, function, coping, and the meaning of safety."},
{id:"ncm-240",q:"A 25-year-old client has been experiencing symptoms of psychosis for the first time. The counselor should:",options:["Begin supportive counseling only","Refer for urgent psychiatric evaluation, engage the family, and consider Coordinated Specialty Care (CST/NAVIGATE)","Tell the client it's just stress","Hospitalize immediately"],answer:1,explanation:"First-episode psychosis: urgent psychiatric evaluation. Coordinate with the family. Consider Coordinated Specialty Care (CST/NAVIGATE) — evidence-based for first-episode psychosis. Components: low-dose antipsychotic, family education, supported employment/education, case management, CBT for psychosis (CBTp). Early intervention improves outcomes. Don't dismiss as stress. Don't hospitalize immediately (depends on safety). Don't just do supportive counseling alone. The duration of untreated psychosis correlates with worse outcomes. Engage the family."},
{id:"ncm-241",q:"A 35-year-old client has been in recovery for opioid use disorder. They are starting a new job. The counselor should:",options:["Tell them to avoid stress","Develop a relapse prevention plan, identify triggers, use coping skills, build the support system, and address the new stressors","Recommend they not work","Hospitalize"],answer:1,explanation:"New job in recovery: support the client's recovery. Develop a relapse prevention plan: identify triggers (people, places, things, emotions), use coping skills (without substances), engage support system (sponsor, AA/NA, friends), and address new stressors. Don't avoid stress (unrealistic). Don't keep them from working (healthy recovery). Don't hospitalize. Celebrate the milestone. Address the new challenges (money, time, identity, coworkers). Build healthy routines."},
{id:"ncm-242",q:"A 14-year-old has been exhibiting symptoms of PTSD after a school shooting. The counselor should:",options:["Use TF-CBT or EMDR (with stabilization first), engage the family, and address the school and community response","Tell the teen to forget it","Refer to a psychiatrist only","Hospitalize"],answer:1,explanation:"Adolescent PTSD after school shooting: TF-CBT or EMDR (with stabilization first). Engage the family. Address the school and community response (postvention). Coordinate with the school. Don't dismiss. Don't refer only to a psychiatrist. Don't hospitalize (rarely appropriate). The counselor's role: support, treatment, and community response. Many adolescents benefit from early intervention. The school shooting is a shared trauma; the whole community needs support. Address: safety, meaning, peers, family, and the future."},
{id:"ncm-243",q:"A 30-year-old client has been dealing with severe anxiety for years. The counselor should:",options:["Recommend benzodiazepines","Conduct a comprehensive assessment, address comorbidities, use CBT (cognitive restructuring, exposure), consider SSRIs/SNRIs, and develop a long-term plan","Hospitalize","Tell them to relax"],answer:1,explanation:"Long-standing anxiety: comprehensive assessment, address comorbidities (depression, substance, OCD, PTSD, medical), use CBT (cognitive restructuring, exposure), consider SSRIs/SNRIs. Develop a long-term plan. Don't recommend benzos (dependence, fall risk, can worsen long-term). Don't hospitalize (rarely appropriate for anxiety alone). Don't tell them to relax (dismissive). The counselor's role: support, treatment, and hope. Many people with long-standing anxiety improve with proper treatment. Address: triggers, function, coping, sleep, and the meaning of safety."},
{id:"ncm-244",q:"A 12-year-old has been exhibiting symptoms of ADHD and has been struggling in school. The counselor should:",options:["Tell the child to focus","Conduct a multi-informant assessment, address the school environment, use behavioral interventions (PMT), consider medication evaluation, and provide school support","Refer to a different counselor","Hospitalize"],answer:1,explanation:"Child ADHD: multi-informant assessment, address the school environment (accommodations, support, classroom strategies), use behavioral interventions (PMT — Parent Management Training), consider medication evaluation (stimulants are first-line; collaborate with child psychiatry). Provide school support. Don't tell the child to focus. Don't refer to a different counselor. Don't hospitalize. The counselor's role: support, family work, school collaboration, and skills. Many children with ADHD improve with proper treatment. Address: family, school, peers, and self-esteem."},
{id:"ncm-245",q:"A 35-year-old client has been struggling with chronic anxiety. The counselor should:",options:["Tell them to relax","Use CBT, address the chronic nature, develop a long-term plan, build coping skills, and address comorbidities","Hospitalize","Refer to a different counselor"],answer:1,explanation:"Chronic anxiety: CBT, address the chronic nature, develop a long-term plan, build coping skills, address comorbidities (depression, substance, sleep). Don't tell them to relax (dismissive). Don't hospitalize. Don't refer to a different counselor. The counselor's role: support, treatment, and hope. Many people with chronic anxiety improve with proper treatment. The work is long-term but rewarding. Address: triggers, function, coping, sleep, and the meaning of safety. The relationship is the basis."},
{id:"ncm-246",q:"A 25-year-old client has been engaging in self-harm. The counselor should:",options:["Hospitalize for every episode","Use DBT, address the function of self-harm, develop alternative coping skills, and address underlying issues","Tell them to stop","Refer to a psychiatrist only"],answer:1,explanation:"Self-harm: DBT is evidence-based. Address the function of self-harm (regulation, communication, dissociation, control). Develop alternative coping skills. Address underlying issues (trauma, BPD, depression, anxiety). Don't hospitalize for every episode (unless imminent risk). Don't tell them to stop. Don't refer only to a psychiatrist. The counselor's role: skills, support, and treatment. Many clients find better ways to manage distress. The work is long-term, but the client can find better ways."},
{id:"ncm-247",q:"A 30-year-old client has been struggling with a new diagnosis of multiple sclerosis. The counselor should:",options:["Refer to a neurologist only","Provide support, use CBT, address grief, engage the family, and collaborate with the medical team","Tell them to stay positive","Recommend ECT"],answer:1,explanation:"Adjustment to MS: provide support, use CBT, address grief (loss of function, identity, future, abilities), engage the family, collaborate with the medical team (neurologist, nurse, OT, PT). Don't refer only to the neurologist. Don't tell them to stay positive (dismissive). Don't recommend ECT (not appropriate). Address: the impact, the uncertainty, the family, the work, the meaning. Many people with MS benefit from counseling and support groups. The counselor's role is key in the adjustment."},
{id:"ncm-248",q:"A 14-year-old has been in a gang. The counselor should:",options:["Report the gang","Engage the teen, assess safety, address reasons for gang involvement, use family therapy, and provide alternatives","Hospitalize","Tell the teen to stop immediately"],answer:1,explanation:"Gang involvement: comprehensive assessment. Safety (the teen and others). Reasons for involvement (belonging, protection, identity, family, money, status). Use MI, family therapy (MDFT, FFT), and provide alternatives (mentorship, programs, school engagement). Don't report the gang (not effective, may damage trust). Don't hospitalize. Don't demand immediate cessation (often increases risk). Address: belonging, family, future, alternatives, and safety. Build the relationship."},
{id:"ncm-249",q:"A 30-year-old client has been in treatment for severe anxiety for 3 months with no improvement. The counselor should:",options:["Terminate treatment","Reassess: diagnosis, treatment fidelity, adherence, comorbidities, the therapeutic alliance, and outside stressors","Switch to a different counselor","Tell the client to work harder"],answer:1,explanation:"Reassess. Common reasons for non-response: incorrect diagnosis, comorbidities (substance, personality, medical), treatment not delivered correctly (fidelity), adherence (medication, homework, session frequency), poor therapeutic alliance, or external stressors. Don't terminate. Don't refer away. Don't blame the client. Consult supervision. Reassess and adjust the plan. Sometimes a different approach or modality is needed. The work is to find what helps. The relationship matters."},
{id:"ncm-250",q:"A 35-year-old client has been sober for 1 year. They are concerned about relapse after a major stressor. The counselor should:",options:["Tell them relapse is part of recovery","Validate the concern, develop a plan to address the stressor without substance use, identify triggers, and use coping skills","Recommend inpatient","Tell them to leave the stressor"],answer:1,explanation:"Sobriety stress: validate the concern, help the client develop a plan to handle the stressor (without substances), identify triggers, and use coping skills. Don't tell them relapse is part of recovery (it's common but not inevitable). Don't recommend inpatient. Don't tell them to leave the stressor. Couples therapy, family therapy, or individual work may be appropriate. Address: communication, problem-solving, recovery support, and emotion regulation. Many people in recovery manage major stressors. The counselor supports the client's continued recovery."},
{id:"ncm-251",q:"A 14-year-old has been in a residential treatment program. The parents are demanding the teen stay longer. The counselor should:",options:["Keep the teen in residential","Base the length of stay on clinical need, work with the family, and develop a transition plan","Discharge immediately","Send to a different program"],answer:1,explanation:"Residential length of stay: based on clinical need, not family pressure. Use clear, individualized treatment goals. Discuss with the family, the team, and the teen. Develop a transition plan. Don't keep them longer than needed (worsens outcomes). Don't discharge abruptly. Don't bounce between programs. Use the family work to address the parents' concerns (e.g., guilt, fear, lack of trust). Effective residential is a step, not a destination."},
{id:"ncm-252",q:"A 30-year-old client has been in a serious car accident and is now unable to work. The counselor should:",options:["Tell them to find a new job","Address the grief, loss, identity, and adjustment; use CBT and supportive counseling; engage the family; and coordinate with the medical and disability team","Hospitalize","Refer to a vocational counselor only"],answer:1,explanation:"Major accident with disability: address the grief, loss of function, identity, role, and adjustment. Use CBT, supportive counseling, and existential work as needed. Engage the family. Coordinate with the medical team, OT/PT, and disability services. Don't tell them to find a new job. Don't hospitalize. Don't refer only to a vocational counselor. The whole person. Many people adjust with proper support. The counselor helps the client find meaning, identity, and engagement despite the changes."},
{id:"ncm-253",q:"A 25-year-old client has been using methamphetamine. The counselor should:",options:["Tell them to stop","Use MI, assess the pattern, address the function, and develop a treatment plan. Consider contingency management (the best evidence-based approach for stimulants)","Hospitalize","Recommend a quick detox"],answer:1,explanation:"Methamphetamine use: MI, assess pattern, function, comorbidities, and consequences. Develop a plan: MI/CBT, contingency management (the best evidence-based approach for stimulants), possibly MAT (no FDA-approved med for meth, but research on mirtazapine, bupropion, naltrexone, modafinil). Address: medical complications (cardiac, dental, psychiatric), sleep, nutrition, psychosis risk. Don't demand immediate abstinence. Don't hospitalize. Don't recommend quick detox. Long-term support."},
{id:"ncm-254",q:"A 12-year-old has been exhibiting symptoms of trauma (nightmares, withdrawal, irritability) after witnessing domestic violence. The counselor should:",options:["Begin trauma processing immediately","Use TF-CBT (Trauma-Focused CBT) or similar — start with psychoeducation, stabilization, and skills, then processing with the family","Tell the child to forget it","Refer to a psychiatrist only"],answer:1,explanation:"Child trauma: TF-CBT is first-line. The PRACTICE model: Psychoeducation, Relaxation, Affect modulation, Cognitive processing, Trauma narrative, In vivo mastery, Conjoint sessions, Enhancing future safety. Don't begin trauma processing without stabilization. Don't dismiss. Don't refer only to a psychiatrist. Address the family. Children process through play, art, and storytelling. The counselor is a key support. The parent who is also affected needs support. Safety is the first priority."},
{id:"ncm-255",q:"A 40-year-old client with severe OCD has been engaging in contamination rituals that take 8 hours per day. The counselor should:",options:["Recommend residential","Build a strong therapeutic relationship, provide psychoeducation, develop a fear hierarchy, and begin ERP","Hospitalize","Tell the client to just stop"],answer:1,explanation:"Severe OCD: build the relationship, provide psychoeducation, develop a fear hierarchy (the most feared item at the top), and begin ERP (gradual exposure with response prevention). SSRIs (often at higher doses) are first-line. Don't recommend residential (often not necessary if the client is willing to do ERP). Don't hospitalize. Don't tell them to 'just stop' (the compulsion is automatic; ERP requires time, support, and motivation). Severe OCD can be treated effectively with intensive ERP + medication. The counselor's patience and support are critical."},
{id:"ncm-256",q:"A 35-year-old client has been dealing with chronic depression for 10 years. The counselor should:",options:["Recommend a quick fix","Provide long-term support, evidence-based therapy (CBT, BA, MBCT, IPT), coordinate with the prescriber, and address chronic issues","Hospitalize","Discharge as chronic"],answer:1,explanation:"Chronic depression: long-term approach. Provide evidence-based therapy (CBT, behavioral activation, MBCT, IPT, CBT for chronic depression). Coordinate with the prescriber. Address: chronic issues, comorbidity, life stress, sleep, exercise, social connection. Don't promise a quick fix. Don't hospitalize (not appropriate for chronic stable depression). Don't discharge as 'chronic' (that abandons the client). Many people with chronic depression can improve with sustained work. The relationship is therapeutic. Stay involved. Don't give up."},
{id:"ncm-257",q:"A 19-year-old client has been engaging in risky sexual behavior. The counselor should:",options:["Tell them to be abstinent","Use MI to explore the behavior, address risk reduction (condom use, STI testing, contraception), and discuss values and goals","Refer to a doctor only","Hospitalize"],answer:1,explanation:"Risky sexual behavior: MI, explore the behavior, address risk reduction (condom use, STI testing, contraception, PrEP for HIV if appropriate), discuss values and goals, address substance use (often related). Don't demand abstinence. Don't refer only to a doctor. Don't hospitalize. Many young people engage in risky behavior. Address: consent, pleasure, relationships, decision-making, self-efficacy, and self-worth. Harm reduction is ethical and effective. Engage the client with respect."},
{id:"ncm-258",q:"A 40-year-old client has been sober for 2 years. They are starting a new relationship. The counselor should:",options:["Tell them to avoid relationships","Explore the client's concerns, develop a plan, address triggers, and support the new relationship","Recommend couples therapy immediately","Hospitalize"],answer:1,explanation:"Recovery and new relationship: explore the client's concerns (early recovery is a vulnerable time). Develop a plan: identify triggers, use coping skills, maintain recovery support, communicate with the partner, attend mutual support, monitor for warning signs. Don't tell them to avoid relationships. Don't recommend couples therapy immediately (let the relationship develop first; couples therapy may be appropriate later). Don't hospitalize. Many people in recovery develop healthy relationships. The counselor supports the client's growth and ongoing recovery."},
{id:"ncm-259",q:"A 28-year-old client has been struggling with anxiety, low self-esteem, and relationship difficulties. The counselor should:",options:["Focus only on anxiety","Conduct a comprehensive assessment and develop an integrated treatment plan that addresses all three areas","Refer to a different counselor","Hospitalize"],answer:1,explanation:"Multiple presenting issues: comprehensive assessment. Integrated treatment plan that addresses anxiety, self-esteem, and relationships. Often one issue is connected to others (e.g., anxiety → avoidance → low self-esteem → relationship problems). CBT often addresses all three (cognitive restructuring, behavioral experiments, social skills). Don't focus only on one. Don't refer away. Don't hospitalize. The whole person. Many clients do well with integrated work. The relationship is the basis."},
{id:"ncm-260",q:"A 45-year-old client has been through a difficult divorce and is struggling with loneliness. The counselor should:",options:["Tell them to find a new relationship","Address the grief, support the client's adjustment, build social connections, and explore values and goals","Refer to a dating app","Hospitalize"],answer:1,explanation:"Post-divorce loneliness: address the grief, support adjustment, build social connections (friends, family, community, groups, activities), explore values and goals. Don't push dating. Don't refer to a dating app. Don't hospitalize. The first year (or two) after divorce is often a time of grief, identity, and rebuilding. The counselor supports the client's growth, not the rush to a new relationship. Many people find meaning and community in this period."},
{id:"ncm-261",q:"A 14-year-old has been refusing to eat and has been losing weight for 3 months. The counselor should FIRST:",options:["Begin family therapy","Conduct a comprehensive assessment (medical, eating behaviors, family, comorbidities) and refer for medical evaluation given the medical risk","Refer to a nutritionist","Tell the family to force meals"],answer:1,explanation:"Adolescent eating disorder: comprehensive assessment (medical, eating behaviors, family, comorbidities) and immediate medical evaluation. Medical risk is real (electrolytes, vital signs, BMI, refeeding risk). Don't just begin family therapy without assessment. Don't refer only to a nutritionist. Don't tell the family to force meals. FBT (Maudsley) is first-line for adolescents, but only after medical stabilization. The counselor is key in engaging the family and supporting recovery."},
{id:"ncm-262",q:"A 30-year-old client has been engaging in self-harm during sessions when distressed. The counselor should:",options:["End the session immediately","Stay with the client (don't leave them alone), use grounding and distress tolerance skills, address the function, and develop a safety plan","Hospitalize for every episode","Tell them to stop"],answer:1,explanation:"Self-harm in session: stay with the client (don't leave them alone). Use grounding, distress tolerance, DBT skills. Address the function. Develop a safety plan. Document. Hospitalize only if imminent risk. Don't end the session abruptly. Don't tell them to stop. Don't shame. The counselor's presence is calming. Many clients use in-session self-harm as a last resort; alternative skills are needed. The relationship and the safety plan are critical. Work with the prescriber if needed."},
{id:"ncm-263",q:"A 19-year-old has been struggling with identity (sexual, gender, career, values). The counselor should:",options:["Tell them to pick one","Support the client's exploration, provide a safe space, address family/cultural factors, and use developmentally appropriate interventions","Recommend a specific identity","Refer to a psychiatrist"],answer:1,explanation:"Adolescent/young adult identity exploration: support the client's exploration. Provide a safe space, address family/cultural factors (which may add stress), use developmentally appropriate interventions (exploration, narrative, person-centered). Many people in late adolescence/early adulthood explore identity (Erikson: identity vs. role confusion). Don't push for a specific identity. Don't tell them to 'pick one' (premature). Don't refer to a psychiatrist (normal developmental process, unless comorbid). The counselor supports the client's growth and discovery."},
{id:"ncm-264",q:"A 35-year-old client has been sober for 5 years. They are now dealing with chronic pain. The counselor should:",options:["Tell them to manage without medication","Address the pain without substance use, collaborate with the medical team, use CBT for chronic pain, and address the risk of relapse","Hospitalize","Recommend opioids"],answer:1,explanation:"Pain in recovery: address without substance use. Collaborate with the medical team. CBT for chronic pain (pacing, activity, sleep, mood, coping). Discuss pain management options (non-opioid preferred, but some patients in recovery can take prescribed opioids with proper support). Don't tell them to manage without medication (pain is real). Don't hospitalize. Don't recommend opioids unilaterally. Address the risk of relapse (high stress). The counselor supports the client's recovery and effective pain management."},
{id:"ncm-265",q:"A 30-year-old client has been experiencing flashbacks and dissociation. The counselor should:",options:["Begin trauma processing immediately","Use a phased approach: stabilization (grounding, safety, coping), then processing (PE, EMDR, CPT), then integration","Tell the client the memories are not real","Hospitalize"],answer:1,explanation:"Flashbacks and dissociation: phased trauma approach. Stabilization first: grounding, safety, coping, regulation. Processing when stable. Integration. Don't begin processing without stabilization (risk of re-traumatization). Don't tell the client the memories are not real (the experience is real). Don't hospitalize (unless imminent risk). Address: the present, the triggers, the body, the relationships, the meaning. The therapeutic relationship is the basis. Many people benefit from a careful, phased approach."},
{id:"ncm-266",q:"A 12-year-old has been exhibiting symptoms of OCD (intrusive thoughts about contamination, washing hands for hours). The counselor should:",options:["Tell the child to stop","Conduct a multi-informant assessment, develop a fear hierarchy, and begin ERP with the family","Refer to a psychiatrist only","Hospitalize"],answer:1,explanation:"Child OCD: multi-informant assessment, family engagement, develop a fear hierarchy, and begin ERP (with the parents as co-therapists). SSRIs are first-line medication (collaborate with child psychiatry). The parents' accommodation is a key target. Don't tell the child to stop. Don't refer only to a psychiatrist. Don't hospitalize. Family-based CBT for OCD is evidence-based. The counselor's patience and the family's support are critical. Many children with OCD improve with proper treatment."},
{id:"ncm-267",q:"A 45-year-old client with chronic depression is in ongoing treatment. They report using alcohol more on weekends. The counselor should:",options:["Tell them to stop","Use MI, assess the use, address the function, and develop a plan based on motivation","Refer to AA immediately","Hospitalize"],answer:1,explanation:"Substance use in chronic depression: MI, assess use, function (coping, sleep, social), motivation, consequences. Develop a plan based on the client's goals (some clients may want moderation, others abstinence; both can be valid). Don't demand abstinence. Don't refer to AA immediately (may not fit). Don't hospitalize (not appropriate for moderate use). Address: depression, sleep, coping, social support. Treat the whole person. Many people with depression benefit from harm reduction."},
{id:"ncm-268",q:"A 25-year-old client with ADHD has been struggling with rejection sensitivity. The counselor should:",options:["Tell them they're too sensitive","Validate the experience, use CBT, address the negative self-talk, and provide skills for emotion regulation","Switch to a different therapy","Hospitalize"],answer:1,explanation:"Rejection Sensitive Dysphoria (RSD) — common in ADHD: validate the experience, use CBT (cognitive restructuring, behavioral experiments), address the negative self-talk, and provide emotion regulation skills. Some clients benefit from medication (often stimulants help; alpha-2 agonists). Don't dismiss. Don't switch. Don't hospitalize. The therapeutic relationship is critical. Address: the past, the present, the relationships, the self-worth, and the skills. Many people with RSD find relief with proper support."},
{id:"ncm-269",q:"A 30-year-old client has been in therapy for depression for 6 weeks. They report partial improvement but still feel hopeless. The counselor should:",options:["Terminate treatment","Continue treatment, reassess (comorbidities, stressors, support, medication), use behavioral activation, and develop a relapse prevention plan","Tell the client to be more positive","Hospitalize"],answer:1,explanation:"Partial improvement: continue. Reassess: comorbidities, stressors, support, sleep, medication adherence, therapeutic alliance. Use behavioral activation. Develop a relapse prevention plan. Don't terminate prematurely. Don't dismiss. Don't hospitalize (unless severe). Many clients improve gradually. The relationship and the structure are important. Some clients need medication augmentation or change. Some need more sessions. Stay involved. Don't give up."},
{id:"ncm-270",q:"A 14-year-old has been experiencing a major depressive episode after a friend's suicide. The counselor should:",options:["Begin trauma processing","Address the depression and grief, monitor for suicide risk, engage the family, and provide trauma-focused support","Hospitalize for safety","Refer to a psychiatrist only"],answer:1,explanation:"Adolescent depression after friend's suicide: assess for suicide risk first. Address the depression and grief. Engage the family. Provide trauma-focused support (TF-CBT, grief work). Don't begin trauma processing without stabilization. Don't hospitalize (unless imminent risk). Don't refer only to a psychiatrist. The combination of depression, grief, and suicide exposure is a serious clinical picture. Postvention is important (school, community). Many adolescents benefit from early intervention."},
{id:"ncm-271",q:"A 35-year-old client has been in long-term recovery from alcohol use disorder. They are now struggling with chronic depression. The counselor should:",options:["Tell them to focus on recovery","Address the depression with evidence-based treatment (CBT, BA, medication referral), coordinate with the recovery support system, and treat the whole person","Recommend more AA meetings","Hospitalize"],answer:1,explanation:"Depression in long-term recovery: treat it. Don't dismiss. Don't tell them to focus only on recovery. Don't recommend more AA (it doesn't treat depression). Don't hospitalize (unless severe). Many people in long-term recovery develop new mental health issues (often related to underlying mood, trauma, life changes). Use CBT, behavioral activation, and medication referral (SSRIs are first-line; bupropion may be preferred for some but beware of seizure risk). Coordinate with the recovery support system. The whole person."},
{id:"ncm-272",q:"A 12-year-old has been engaging in bullying online (cyberbullying). The counselor should FIRST:",options:["Take away the device","Conduct a comprehensive assessment, address the behavior, engage the family, collaborate with the school, and teach digital citizenship","Hospitalize","Tell the parents to monitor more"],answer:1,explanation:"Cyberbullying: comprehensive assessment. Why is the child bullying? (Modeling, peer dynamics, social skills deficits, trauma, conduct disorder, ADHD). Address the behavior, engage the family, collaborate with the school, and teach digital citizenship. Don't take away the device (without addressing the underlying issue). Don't hospitalize. Don't rely on more parental monitoring (often ineffective). The victim also needs support. Many cases resolve with intervention. The counselor is key."},
{id:"ncm-273",q:"A 50-year-old client has been dealing with severe chronic mental illness for 20 years. They want to live independently. The counselor should:",options:["Tell them they can't","Assess their current functioning, develop a supported housing plan, coordinate with ACT or case management, and support the client's goal","Hospitalize","Refer to a nursing home"],answer:1,explanation:"Recovery goal: independent living. Assess functioning, develop a supported housing plan (Housing First is evidence-based), coordinate with ACT (Assertive Community Treatment) or case management, and support the client's goal. Don't dismiss. Don't hospitalize. Don't refer to a nursing home. Many people with severe mental illness can live independently with proper support. The counselor supports the client's autonomy and choice. The recovery model emphasizes hope, empowerment, and community."},
{id:"ncm-274",q:"A 19-year-old has been engaging in self-harm. The counselor should:",options:["Hospitalize for every episode","Use DBT, address the function of self-harm, develop alternative coping skills, and address underlying issues","Tell them to stop","Refer to a psychiatrist only"],answer:1,explanation:"Self-harm: DBT is evidence-based. Address the function of self-harm (regulation, communication, dissociation, control). Develop alternative coping skills. Address underlying issues (trauma, BPD, depression, anxiety). Don't hospitalize for every episode (unless imminent risk). Don't tell them to stop. Don't refer only to a psychiatrist. The counselor's role: skills, support, and treatment. Many clients find better ways to manage distress. The work is long-term, but the client can find better ways."},
{id:"ncm-275",q:"A 35-year-old client has been dealing with chronic pain for 5 years. They are on long-term opioids. The counselor should:",options:["Tell them to stop immediately","Address the chronic pain with CBT, collaborate with the pain team, discuss a slow taper if appropriate, and treat comorbid depression or anxiety","Hospitalize","Increase the dose"],answer:1,explanation:"Chronic opioid use: address comorbid mental health, use CBT for chronic pain, coordinate with the pain team. Discuss a slow taper if appropriate (CDC guidelines, slower for long-term users), with monitoring for withdrawal, increased pain, and suicide risk. Don't force. Don't increase. Don't hospitalize. Many patients on long-term opioids have hyperalgesia. Engage the prescriber. The functional goal is improvement in function, not zero pain. Address the meaning, coping, and impact. The counselor's role: support, treatment, and hope."},
{id:"ncm-276",q:"A 14-year-old has been refusing to leave the house due to severe social anxiety. The counselor should FIRST:",options:["Recommend homeschooling","Conduct a comprehensive assessment and develop a graded return-to-school and social plan using CBT and exposure","Hospitalize","Tell the parents to force attendance"],answer:1,explanation:"Comprehensive assessment: social anxiety severity, comorbidities (depression, other anxiety, OCD, autism), school environment, family dynamics. Develop a graduated exposure plan: home, then small outings, then school. CBT (cognitive restructuring, social skills, exposure) + SSRIs. Engage the family and school. Don't force attendance. Don't recommend homeschooling (worsens anxiety). Don't hospitalize (rarely). Address the avoidance pattern early; it worsens with time."},
{id:"ncm-277",q:"A 30-year-old client has been dealing with severe anxiety and has been unable to work. The counselor should:",options:["Tell them to push through","Conduct a comprehensive assessment, use CBT (cognitive restructuring, exposure), consider SSRIs, and develop a graded return-to-work plan","Hospitalize","Recommend disability"],answer:1,explanation:"Severe anxiety: comprehensive assessment, use CBT (cognitive restructuring, exposure), consider SSRIs. Develop a graded return-to-work plan. Don't tell them to push through (anxiety is real). Don't hospitalize. Don't recommend disability (premature; many people can return to work with proper treatment). The counselor's role: support, treatment, and hope. Many people with severe anxiety improve with proper treatment. Address: family, work, identity, and the meaning of engagement."},
{id:"ncm-278",q:"A 50-year-old client has been sober for 10 years. They are now dealing with a new mental health concern. The counselor should:",options:["Tell them recovery is more important","Address the new concern with appropriate treatment, in coordination with the recovery support system","Send back to AA","Hospitalize"],answer:1,explanation:"New mental health concern in long-term recovery: address it. The counselor provides appropriate treatment (CBT, BA, medication referral if needed) while honoring the recovery journey. Coordinate with the recovery support system. Don't dismiss the new concern. Don't just send back to AA. Don't hospitalize (rarely). Many people in long-term recovery have new mental health issues (anxiety, depression, trauma). Recovery is holistic. Treat the whole person. Engage the medical team as needed."},
{id:"ncm-279",q:"A 30-year-old client has been in treatment for anxiety and depression for 3 months. The counselor should:",options:["Terminate treatment","Continue treatment, reassess progress, develop a relapse prevention plan, and discuss maintenance and termination collaboratively","Increase the dose","Tell them they're cured"],answer:1,explanation:"Anxiety and depression treatment at 3 months: continue treatment, reassess progress, develop a relapse prevention plan, and discuss maintenance and termination collaboratively. Don't terminate prematurely. Don't increase unnecessarily. Don't tell them they're cured. The work is to consolidate the gains, prepare for setbacks, and end well. Many clients benefit from booster sessions. The counselor supports the client's growth and continued well-being. Address: triggers, function, coping, and the meaning of safety."},
{id:"ncm-280",q:"A 12-year-old has been exhibiting symptoms of ADHD. The parents are skeptical of medication. The counselor should:",options:["Force medication","Provide accurate information, address the parents' concerns, discuss behavioral interventions (PMT), and respect the family's decision","Tell them they must medicate","Refer to a different counselor"],answer:1,explanation:"ADHD and parental skepticism: provide accurate information, address concerns, discuss the evidence for medication AND behavioral interventions (PMT, school supports, accommodations), and respect the family's decision. Don't force. Don't dismiss. Don't refer away. The therapeutic relationship is important. Many parents' concerns are valid (medication isn't the only option). Address the impact on the child's functioning. The counselor is an educator and advocate for the child."},
{id:"ncm-281",q:"A 40-year-old client with severe OCD has been hospitalized due to severe contamination fears and rituals. The counselor in the hospital should:",options:["Reinforce the rituals to reduce anxiety","Conduct a brief assessment, begin or continue intensive ERP, and discharge to intensive outpatient or residential care","Tell the client they're fine","Recommend a medication change without coordination"],answer:1,explanation:"OCD inpatient: not the right setting for routine OCD treatment (often reinforces rituals). Best: brief assessment, support medication, begin or continue intensive ERP if the client is willing, and discharge to intensive outpatient, residential, or day treatment for ongoing ERP. The inpatient stay is brief. Don't reinforce the rituals. Don't dismiss. Don't change meds without coordination with the outpatient team. Plan for ongoing intensive treatment. ERP is the most effective, even when severe."},
{id:"ncm-282",q:"A 30-year-old client has been in treatment for severe anxiety for 1 year. The counselor should:",options:["Terminate treatment","Discuss maintenance, relapse prevention, and termination collaboratively","Increase session frequency","Tell the client they're cured"],answer:1,explanation:"Long-term anxiety recovery: discuss maintenance, relapse prevention (warning signs, coping skills, supports, professional numbers), and termination collaboratively. Don't terminate prematurely. Don't increase frequency unnecessarily. Don't tell the client they're cured (anxiety disorders are often chronic and recurrent). The work is to consolidate the gains, prepare for setbacks, and end well. Many clients benefit from booster sessions. The counselor supports the client's continued well-being."},
{id:"ncm-283",q:"A 14-year-old has been suicidal and is now stabilized. The counselor should:",options:["Discharge from treatment","Develop an ongoing safety plan, address underlying issues, engage the family, and continue regular therapy","Hospitalize for months","Tell the teen they're fine"],answer:1,explanation:"After stabilization: ongoing care. Safety plan, family engagement, individual therapy (DBT, CBT, family therapy), address underlying issues, school support, and peer support. Don't discharge (transition is high-risk). Don't hospitalize for months (acute stabilization is brief). Don't tell the teen they're fine. Build the relationship, address the meaning, monitor for warning signs, and continue treatment. The work continues. Many teens do well with proper support."},
{id:"ncm-284",q:"A 35-year-old client has been in recovery for alcohol use disorder. They are now in a high-stress job. The counselor should:",options:["Tell them to quit the job","Develop a stress management plan, address triggers, maintain recovery support, and use coping skills","Recommend inpatient","Hospitalize"],answer:1,explanation:"Recovery in a high-stress job: develop a stress management plan (without substances), address triggers, maintain recovery support (sponsor, AA, friends), use coping skills, ensure self-care, monitor for warning signs. Don't tell them to quit (work is a protective factor; may not be financially feasible). Don't recommend inpatient. Don't hospitalize. Many people in recovery manage high-stress jobs. The counselor supports the client's continued recovery and quality of life."},
{id:"ncm-285",q:"A 25-year-old client has been diagnosed with schizoaffective disorder. The counselor should:",options:["Tell the client they have schizophrenia","Provide education about schizoaffective disorder, support medication adherence, address the mood symptoms, and use CBTp","Refer to a psychiatrist only","Hospitalize"],answer:1,explanation:"Schizoaffective: psychotic symptoms + a major mood episode. Education, support medication adherence, address both psychotic and mood symptoms. CBTp + CBT for the mood component. Coordination with the prescriber. Family education. Don't tell the client they have schizophrenia (inaccurate). Don't refer only to a psychiatrist. Don't hospitalize (unless acute). The counselor provides psychotherapy and support. Many people with schizoaffective do well with integrated treatment."},
{id:"ncm-286",q:"A 35-year-old client has been in treatment for PTSD for 1 year with good progress. They report a new stressor and worsening symptoms. The counselor should:",options:["Tell them to use what they learned","Validate the regression, address the new stressor, reinforce skills, and use this as a learning opportunity","Switch to a different therapy","Hospitalize"],answer:1,explanation:"PTSD recovery: setbacks are normal. Validate, don't shame. Address the new stressor, reinforce the skills the client has, use this as a learning opportunity, and adjust the treatment plan if needed. Don't dismiss. Don't switch to a different therapy (PE/EMDR/CPT is still the best). Don't hospitalize (unless severe). Many people experience setbacks in recovery. The relationship and the skills are the basis. Treat the temporary setback as part of the long-term process."},
{id:"ncm-287",q:"A 30-year-old client has been in treatment for severe anxiety for 1 year. The counselor should:",options:["Terminate treatment","Discuss maintenance, relapse prevention, and termination collaboratively","Increase session frequency","Tell the client they're cured"],answer:1,explanation:"Long-term anxiety recovery: discuss maintenance, relapse prevention (warning signs, coping skills, supports, professional numbers), and termination collaboratively. Don't terminate prematurely. Don't increase frequency unnecessarily. Don't tell the client they're cured (anxiety disorders are often chronic and recurrent). The work is to consolidate the gains, prepare for setbacks, and end well. Many clients benefit from booster sessions. The counselor supports the client's continued well-being."},
{id:"ncm-288",q:"A 12-year-old has been exhibiting symptoms of trauma after witnessing domestic violence. The counselor should:",options:["Begin trauma processing immediately","Use TF-CBT (Trauma-Focused CBT) or similar — start with psychoeducation, stabilization, and skills, then processing with the family","Tell the child to forget it","Refer to a psychiatrist only"],answer:1,explanation:"Child trauma: TF-CBT is first-line. The PRACTICE model: Psychoeducation, Relaxation, Affect modulation, Cognitive processing, Trauma narrative, In vivo mastery, Conjoint sessions, Enhancing future safety. Don't begin trauma processing without stabilization. Don't dismiss. Don't refer only to a psychiatrist. Address the family. Children process through play, art, and storytelling. The counselor is a key support. The parent who is also affected needs support. Safety is the first priority."},
{id:"ncm-289",q:"A 40-year-old client with chronic insomnia has been using over-the-counter sleep aids nightly. The counselor should:",options:["Tell them to keep using","Address the OTC use (long-term safety concerns, tolerance), recommend CBT-I, and discuss tapering with the prescriber","Hospitalize","Refer to a sleep clinic only"],answer:1,explanation:"OTC sleep aids (antihistamines like diphenhydramine): long-term safety concerns (tolerance, anticholinergic effects, falls, cognitive effects in older adults). Recommend CBT-I (first-line, durable). Discuss tapering with the prescriber. Don't dismiss. Don't hospitalize. Don't refer only to a sleep clinic. Many people rely on OTC sleep aids. Address the underlying insomnia. Treat the whole person. Engage the medical team."},
{id:"ncm-290",q:"A 30-year-old client has been engaging in self-harm. The counselor should:",options:["Hospitalize for every episode","Use DBT, address the function of self-harm, develop alternative coping skills, and address underlying issues","Tell them to stop","Refer to a psychiatrist only"],answer:1,explanation:"Self-harm: DBT is evidence-based. Address the function of self-harm (regulation, communication, dissociation, control). Develop alternative coping skills. Address underlying issues (trauma, BPD, depression, anxiety). Don't hospitalize for every episode (unless imminent risk). Don't tell them to stop. Don't refer only to a psychiatrist. The counselor's role: skills, support, and treatment. Many clients find better ways to manage distress. The work is long-term, but the client can find better ways."},
{id:"ncm-291",q:"A 35-year-old client has been struggling with chronic anxiety and has been on benzodiazepines for years. The counselor should:",options:["Tell them to stop immediately","Discuss a slow taper, recommend CBT and SSRI, and coordinate with the prescriber","Increase the dose","Switch to alcohol"],answer:1,explanation:"Long-term benzodiazepines: not recommended (dependence, falls, cognitive effects, rebound anxiety on stopping). The counselor discusses a slow taper (withdrawal can be life-threatening — seizures). Coordinate with the prescriber. Recommend CBT and SSRI/SNRI. Don't stop abruptly. Don't increase. Don't replace with alcohol (much worse). Address: reasons for use, alternatives, anxiety, and sleep."},
{id:"ncm-292",q:"A 30-year-old client has been in treatment for severe OCD for 1 year. The counselor should:",options:["Terminate treatment","Discuss maintenance, relapse prevention, and termination collaboratively. Many clients need ongoing ERP or maintenance medication.","Increase session frequency","Tell the client they're cured"],answer:1,explanation:"Long-term OCD recovery: discuss maintenance, relapse prevention (warning signs, coping skills, supports, professional numbers, ERP booster sessions), and termination collaboratively. Many clients need ongoing low-dose ERP or maintenance medication. Don't terminate prematurely. Don't increase frequency unnecessarily. Don't tell the client they're cured (OCD is often chronic and recurrent). The work is to consolidate the gains, prepare for setbacks, and end well."},
{id:"ncm-293",q:"A 25-year-old client has been dealing with severe anxiety and has been unable to work. The counselor should:",options:["Tell them to push through","Conduct a comprehensive assessment, use CBT (cognitive restructuring, exposure), consider SSRIs, and develop a graded return-to-work plan","Hospitalize","Recommend disability"],answer:1,explanation:"Severe anxiety: comprehensive assessment, use CBT (cognitive restructuring, exposure), consider SSRIs. Develop a graded return-to-work plan. Don't tell them to push through (anxiety is real). Don't hospitalize. Don't recommend disability (premature; many people can return to work with proper treatment). The counselor's role: support, treatment, and hope. Many people with severe anxiety improve with proper treatment. Address: family, work, identity, and the meaning of engagement."},
{id:"ncm-294",q:"A 35-year-old client has been sober for 1 year. They are concerned about relapse after a major stressor. The counselor should:",options:["Tell them relapse is part of recovery","Validate the concern, develop a plan to address the stressor without substance use, identify triggers, and use coping skills","Recommend inpatient","Tell them to leave the stressor"],answer:1,explanation:"Sobriety stress: validate the concern, help the client develop a plan to handle the stressor (without substances), identify triggers, and use coping skills. Don't tell them relapse is part of recovery (it's common but not inevitable). Don't recommend inpatient. Don't tell them to leave the stressor. Couples therapy, family therapy, or individual work may be appropriate. Address: communication, problem-solving, recovery support, and emotion regulation. Many people in recovery manage major stressors. The counselor supports the client's continued recovery."},
{id:"ncm-295",q:"A 14-year-old has been in a gang. The counselor should:",options:["Report the gang","Engage the teen, assess safety, address reasons for gang involvement, use family therapy, and provide alternatives","Hospitalize","Tell the teen to stop immediately"],answer:1,explanation:"Gang involvement: comprehensive assessment. Safety (the teen and others). Reasons for involvement (belonging, protection, identity, family, money, status). Use MI, family therapy (MDFT, FFT), and provide alternatives (mentorship, programs, school engagement). Don't report the gang (not effective, may damage trust). Don't hospitalize. Don't demand immediate cessation (often increases risk). Address: belonging, family, future, alternatives, and safety. Build the relationship."},
{id:"ncm-296",q:"A 30-year-old client has been in a serious car accident and is now unable to work. The counselor should:",options:["Tell them to find a new job","Address the grief, loss, identity, and adjustment; use CBT and supportive counseling; engage the family; and coordinate with the medical and disability team","Hospitalize","Refer to a vocational counselor only"],answer:1,explanation:"Major accident with disability: address the grief, loss of function, identity, role, and adjustment. Use CBT, supportive counseling, and existential work as needed. Engage the family. Coordinate with the medical team, OT/PT, and disability services. Don't tell them to find a new job. Don't hospitalize. Don't refer only to a vocational counselor. The whole person. Many people adjust with proper support. The counselor helps the client find meaning, identity, and engagement despite the changes."},
{id:"ncm-297",q:"A 25-year-old client has been using methamphetamine. The counselor should:",options:["Tell them to stop","Use MI, assess the pattern, address the function, and develop a treatment plan. Consider contingency management (the best evidence-based approach for stimulants)","Hospitalize","Recommend a quick detox"],answer:1,explanation:"Methamphetamine use: MI, assess pattern, function, comorbidities, and consequences. Develop a plan: MI/CBT, contingency management (the best evidence-based approach for stimulants), possibly MAT (no FDA-approved med for meth, but research on mirtazapine, bupropion, naltrexone, modafinil). Address: medical complications (cardiac, dental, psychiatric), sleep, nutrition, psychosis risk. Don't demand immediate abstinence. Don't hospitalize. Don't recommend quick detox. Long-term support."},
{id:"ncm-298",q:"A 30-year-old client has been in treatment for severe depression for 1 year with good progress. The counselor should:",options:["Terminate immediately","Discuss maintenance, relapse prevention, and termination collaboratively","Increase session frequency","Tell the client they're cured"],answer:1,explanation:"Long-term recovery: discuss maintenance (continue for a while to consolidate), relapse prevention (warning signs, coping skills, supports, professional numbers), and termination collaboratively. Don't terminate immediately. Don't increase frequency. Don't tell the client they're cured (depression often recurs). The relationship is the basis. Many clients benefit from maintenance. The counselor supports the client's continued growth and well-being. End well. Address: identity, meaning, and the future."},
{id:"ncm-299",q:"A 14-year-old has been engaging in self-harm. The parents are in denial. The counselor should:",options:["Tell the parents the teen is fine","Address the self-harm, engage the family, provide education, develop a safety plan, and provide family therapy","Hospitalize","Discharge the case"],answer:1,explanation:"Self-harm with parental denial: address the self-harm, engage the family, provide education (what self-harm is, what it isn't, what the teen needs), develop a safety plan, and provide family therapy. Don't tell the parents the teen is fine. Don't hospitalize (unless imminent risk). Don't discharge. The counselor's role: engage the family, address the family dynamics (denial, shame, fear), and provide treatment. Many parents of self-harming teens struggle with guilt, fear, and shame. The work is to engage them and provide treatment. The teen's safety is the first priority."},
{id:"ncm-300",q:"A 35-year-old client with severe depression has been resistant to multiple treatments. The counselor should:",options:["Discharge as untreatable","Continue to provide therapy, re-evaluate the diagnosis and treatment, consider TMS/esketamine/MAOIs/lithium augmentation, and coordinate with the team","Tell them to be more positive","Recommend ECT immediately"],answer:1,explanation:"Treatment-resistant depression: continue. Re-evaluate: diagnosis, comorbidities, treatment adherence, therapeutic alliance, and treatment fidelity. Consider alternative treatments (TMS, esketamine, MAOIs, lithium augmentation, atypical antipsychotic augmentation, ECT). Coordinate with the psychiatrist. Don't discharge. Don't dismiss. Don't immediately recommend ECT (usually after multiple trials). Stay involved. The counselor is an important anchor. Many 'treatment-resistant' cases respond with persistence and a fresh approach."}
);
